column58: Gasket; Manway or Dome Cover; Vacuum Relief Valve
column62: Defective Component or Device; Improper Preparation for Transportation; Deterioration or Aging
column168: A crew working with the rail car stated that they smelled an odor coming from the car when they went to move it. Once it was assumed that the car was possibly leaking the car was moved out of the area and onto a rip track located at the south end of the yard. Upon investigation it was discovered that there were 3 manway bolts that were less than tool tight and also the gasket was bad. The 3 manway bolts were tightened and the gasket was replaced. The next morning myself and my contractor Response Management Services went back out to check the car one more time. At this time it was discovered that the Vacuum relief device was bad as well. The VRD was replaced and the subsequent vapor release was stopped. The shipper was advised that the car will need an OTMA to move on to home shop.
column169: I spoke with Safety-Kleen/ Clean Harbors and advised that more thorough inspections and shipping procedures should be done in order the prevent these leaks.

On November 02, 2018, a while during loading operations a Schneider Bulk Carriers tractor trailer experienced a cargo release of UN3266, Ecolab Questar CAF to the underlying asphalt. A nearby drain was impacted. On November 02, 2018, at 0437 EST HazChem personnel arrived onsite and stated an estimates 20 gallons of UN3266 released into the storm drain on site. The impacted area on the asphalt measured 70' x 15'. Contractor estimated about 30-40 gallons of product released in total. A vac truck was brought out on site and pumped 100gal of water out of the drain. The contractor stated that the product that was released to the drain was contained to the bottom and there were no further signs of migration. Absorbents were used to clean the asphalt and 2-55gal poly drums of waste were generated. All waste was taken off site for proper disposal.

column168: An odor was reported near UTLX 954327. Vapor was releasing at the Pressure Relief Device retainer. The stem and seat O-rings were replaced. This stopped the vapor release.

column168: On 11/8/18 at 0041 hours ET Scott Stoneburg from XPO Logistics, contacted ERTS in regards to a hazardous release,  located at Terminal USU in Salt Lake City, UT. It was reported that (1) 1-gallon poly jug of Isopropyl Alcohol 99% was damaged due to improper loading from domicile terminal UBY. Approximately 6 ounces released to the floor of trailer #3153084. Terminal personnel placed the impacted absorbents and damaged jug into a 30-gallon steel drum with a poly liner and stored the drum in the facilities waste area.

On 11/9/18 at 0230 hours ET Martin Gough from XPO Logistics, contacted ERTS in regards to a hazardous release,  located at Terminal XDE in Romulus, MI. It was reported that (1) 55 gallon metal drum of Z Guard 1021 FR was damaged due to a forklift accident, releasing approximately 2 gallons to the floor of trailer #3133299. Terminal personnel placed the impacted absorbents into a 20 gallon steel drum and damaged drum into an 85 gallon steel drum with a poly liner, both stored in the facilities waste area for terminal personnel to manage.

At 2140 ET, 11/09/2018, ERTS received a call from Arthur of Road Runner Transportation Systems regarding a spill at the terminal. It was reported at 2100 ET, terminal personal were transporting a product when a forklift punctured a single 55-gallon drum containing NA1993 "Towerdraw AA-604", in turn releasing 1 cup of the product to the dock floor. Terminal personnel immediately flipped the punctured drum to stop the product from spilling. The punctured drum was over-packed and returned to the shipper. The impacted absorbents were placed in a separate waste drum.

On 11/9/18 at 0247 hours ET Jason Page from XPO Logistics, contacted ERTS in regards to a hazardous release, located at Terminal XCN in West Chester, OH. It was reported that (1) 55 gallon metal drum of UN3082 Radicool SF-O Pre-Mix was damaged due to a faulty skid causing the drum to collapse to the floor, releasing approximately 4 ounces to the floor of the concrete dock. Terminal personnel placed the impacted absorbents and damaged drum into an 85 gallon poly drum with a poly liner and stored it in the facilities waste area for terminal personnel to manage.

At 0251 EST, Christopher Sain with XPO Logistics terminal UBY contacted ERTS regarding a cargo release. It was reported that (1) 5-gallon metal pail fell in transit causing the release of approximately 1 gallon of UN1993 Flammable liquid, n.o.s, 3, PGII "Service Pro Brake Cleaner". Terminal personnel placed the damaged pail and impacted absorbents into a 35-gallon metal drum in the facilities waste area for terminal personnel to manage.

I found a blue composite hard shell rectangular box with clasps that appeared worn& rusty. The shipper had wrapped filament tape around the box to secure the clasps. There were two placards with writing on it that suggested it was a dewar for Liquid Oxygen, UN 1073. Additionally, the blue inside box was not marked to be in compliance as a DOT-31FP. The freight was held pending an FAA inspection. FAA MEM SECFO Hazmat Manager Stan Satchell was notified electronically.

column168: The tank car was reported leaking by UPRR yard employees. Manager of Hazardous Materials Tom Robinson was called for a response. Manager Robinson inspected the car and found the top operated bottom outlet valve was not closed all the way allowing the product to leak into the secondary valve on the bottom of the car. The plug on the secondary valve was also loose allowing product to drip to the ground. The top operated bottom outlet valve was properly secured and the plug on the secondary valve was tightened properly. The spillage was neutralized and remediated. The shipper acquired an OTMA for the car to be brought back to Axiall to be unloaded and repaired.

The tank car was reported to have liquid dripping from the top down the side of the car. Manager of Hazardous Materials Tom Robinson was called for a response. Manager Robinson inspected the car and found the leak was coming from a loose liquid valve that was threaded into the eduction line. The valve was tightened and the spillage was remediated. The shipper is obtaining an OTMA for the car to move to be unloaded and then properly repaired.

column168: At 1919 ERTS was contacted by Brandon Hamer of XPO Logistics NMP about a cargo release. It was reported that due to a forklift puncture approximately 5 gallons of UN3266, 8, II FM 618-ES Power Wash released from a 55 gallon poly drum. The caller stated that the released product was contained to the trailer. ERTS reviewed the SDS with the caller and it was determined a contractor needed to be sent. Contractor arrived on site and determined that the release impacted a 5x10 ft. area of the trailer floor and an area similar in size underneath the trailer. The spill was cleaned up using pads, oil dry and neutralizer before being overpacked into poly drums. The originally damaged 55 gallon poly drum was placed in a 95 gallon poly overpack while the impacted oil dry and pads were placed in a 55 gallon poly drum. The waste was left on site for XPO logistics to handle. There were no drains, soils, or waterways impacted by the release. There is no further clean up needed.

column168: At 0038 ERTS was contacted by Zach Hansen of XPO Logistics XHG about a cargo release. It was reported that due to improper loading approximately 5 gallons of UN2794, 8, III battery acid released from a multiple industrial batteries. The caller stated that the released product was contained to the trailer. ERTS reviewed the situation with the caller and it was determined a contractor needed to be sent. Contractor confirmed that 10 gallons of product had release from (3) 20 gallon industrial sized batteries. The release was contained to the trailer floor. Contractor repalatized the damaged batteries and placed them in the OS&D area. The released material was cleaned off of the trailer floor using baking soda and absorbents. There is no further cleanup needed.

column168: ACCIDENT OCCURRED ON A VERY NARROW SECONDARY ROAD. OUR DRIVER LEFT A STOP AT 201 SPRING ST. AND WAS ON ROUTE TO NEXT STOP. APPROXIMATELY 200 YARDS FROM 201 THE TRUCK STARTED TO LEAVE THE ROAD ON THE PASSENGER SIDE OF THE VEHICLE. THE TRUCK TRAVELED 150' WITH THE PASSENGER SIDE TIRES IN THE MUD ON THE SIDE OF THE ROAD, WHEN THE TRUCK FINALLY GOT BACK ON THE PAVEMENT THE TRUCK SHOT ACROSS THE ROAD STRUCK A TREE AND SPUN AROUND SO THAT NOSE OF THE VEHICLE WAS HEADING IN THE OPPOSITE DIRECTION FROM IT'S PREVIOUS TRAVEL DIRECTION. THE TRUCK LANDED ON IT'S PASSENGER SIDE.  THE CAB WAS DEMOLISHED, THE PROPANE TANK WAS DENTED, BUT NOT COMPROMISED. THE FORCE OF THE IMPACT WITH THE GROUND SNAPPED THE BACK CHECK VALVE IN HALF WHERE IT ENTERED THE TANK. EVEN THOUGH THE EXTERIOR PORTION OF THE VALVE WAS DAMAGED THE BACK CHECK PERFORMED IT'S INTENDED JOB OF CONTROLLING THE AMOUNT OF LEAKAGE, THE VALVE HAS A SMALL HOLE (#56 DRILL SIZE) TO ALLOW PRESSURE TO EQUALIZE BETWEEN PORTIONS OF THE PIPING. PROPANE IS ALSO A REFRIGERANT, SO THERE WAS A LARGE AMOUNT OF FROST OF FROST AT THE POINT OF THE LEAK MAKING AN ACCURATE DIAGNOSIS OF THE DAMAGE DIFFICULT. BECAUSE OF THIS WE COULD NOT TELL THE TOTAL AMOUNT OF DAMAGE TO THE PIPING.  THE DECISION WAS MADE TO TAKE THE SAFEST REMEDIATION WHICH WAS TO TOTALLY EVACUATE THE CONTENTS OF THE TRUCK. WE WERE ABLE TO PUMP APPROXIMATELY 600 GALLONS INTO ANOTHER TRUCK, AND THE REST OF THE LOAD WAS BURNED OFF. THE TANK WA SPURGE WITH WATER BEFORE RIGHTING THE TRUCK. THIS PROCESS WAS THE SAFEST BUT ALSO THE LONGEST IN TIME, ACCOUNTING FOR THE LENGTH OF THE INCIDENT.
column169: WE WILL BE INCREASING OUR TRAINING FOR DRIVERS IN THIS AREA.  THE PACKAGING WILL BE LOOKED AT AND HAS BEEN LOOKED AT TO SEE IF WE CAN IMPROVE THE PERFORMANCE OF THE PIPING IN ROLLOVER SITUATIONS. THERE ARE ONLY A FEW COMPANIES MANUFACTURING PROPANE BOBTAILS, AND WE WILL BE DISCUSSING THIS CRASH WITH THEM.

column168: Terminal employee was in the process of loading product through the trailer manway with a false manway cover.  Terminal employee noticed product spillage from the trailer manway and used the stop button to stop the pump and flow of product.  The spilled product flowed into the trailer crash box then through the crash box drain tubes into a spill pan placed under the trailer before the loading process was started.  An estimated 20 gallons was captured in the spill pans with 5 gallons impacting the ground.  Due to inclement weather the employee miss identified the gallons on the meter.  The employee read the meter as 6000 gallons when the meter was actually at 8000 gallons.  The pump was equipped with a high level cut-off probe but the probe was not working properly and was taken out of service.
column169: The use of a high level alarm was implemented until the High level cut-off probe was repaired.  Additional training was provided on body positioning during inclement weather for better visibility of the meter.

column168: On November 14, 2018, at 0319 ET, XPO Logistics contacted ERTS to report a hazardous release. It was reported that (1) 1 gallon poly jug HCT waterSolv was damaged due to unknown events. Approximately 1-gallon of UN3265 HCT Water Solv released to the floor of trailer #3115075. ERTS dispatched H2O Environmental to the site to complete clean up and over packing operations. On November 15, 2018, at 0033 ET, contractors arrived onsite. Contractor located (1) 5-gallon poly jug with an estimated 1 gallon of product released due to the bottom of the jug experiencing a puncture. The jug was turned upside down prior to the contractors arrival.  Ar 0120 ET, contractor stated the area on the trailer floor measured 1' x 1' and the product was dried. At 0140 ET, contractor stated terminal personnel reloaded the trailer fully due to the release being dried. Contractor generated (1) 20-gallon poly drum and staged the waste in the terminals waste area for terminal personnel to manage and then departed site.

On November 22, 2018, at 0148 ET, ERTS was notified by XPO Logistics of a hazardous release. It was stated that due to there being a nail in the pallet, approximately 5-ounces of UN Inhibitor AZ1804 released from a 5-gallon metal pail to the dock floor. ERTS dispatched ERS of OK to conduct all onsite cleanup and over packing operations. At 0700 ET, contractors arrive onsite and located the damaged container.  Contractors over packed the pail into a 55-gallon poly drum and applied citric acid powder to the impacted dock to neutralize the release. pH paper returned a neutral reading.  At 0740 ET, contractors completed all work and departed site. One 55-gallon poly drum containing PPE, impacted absorbents, neutralizing agent, and the damaged freight was placed into the terminals waste area for terminal personnel to manage.

column62: Missing Component or Device; Human Error
column168: ON 11-01-18 DISPATCH OF 7500 GALLONS WAS REQUESTED FOR RYDER TRUCK RENTAL AT 7425 WEST PARK IN BEAUMONT, TX. UPON ARRIVAL, DRIVER DAVID BILL STUCK THE ABOVE GROUND TANK AT 31 INCHES AND THEN ASKED TWO RYDER EMPLOYEES FRO THE ATG READING. THEY VERIFIED THAT THE LOAD WOULD FIT AND THE READING WAS 31.5 INCHES. THEIR WAS NO PAPER IN THE ATG TO GIVE HIM A COPY. THE ISLAND ATTENDANT CONFIRMED THAT 7500 GALS WOULD FIT. AT 7200 GALLONS THE DIESEL STARTED TO COME OUT OF AN OPEN 2 INCH LID ON TOP OF THE TANK. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT OFF THE PUMP AND VALVES. HE CONTAINED THE SPILL WITH PADS AND SOCKS. HE THEN CALLED THE DISPATCHER AND RANDY STATLER (VP OF SAFETY). THE ENVIRONMENTAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM OMI WAS SENT TO THE SITE FOR FULL REMOVAL AND CLEANUP. INITIAL ESTIMATES OF SPILL WERE 58 GALLONS AND OMI ESTIMATED IT AT 70 GALLONS, SINCE TANK WAS OVERFILLED STICK READING AND ATG WERE NOT ACCURATE. 202 GALLONS STILL ON THE TANKER WERE RETAINED TO ANOTHER LOCATION. FUEL DID NOT LEAVE THE CONCRETE SLAB OR ENTER ANY WATER WAYS.
column169: SUGGESTIONS 1. INSTALLATION OF A 90% OVERFILL ALARM WOULD HAVE PREVENTED THIS OVERFILL 2. TOP TWO INCH OPENING SHOULD BE CLOSED. NOT A VENT. 3. SIGN ON TANK SAYS CAPACITY 7500 GALLONS. THEY ORDER 7500 GALLONS? 4. THEIR IS NO CONTAINMENT AROUND THIS TANK FOR SPILLS OR OVERFILLS.

column168: On 11/08/2018, at 0924 hours, a Federal Railroad Administration Hazardous Materials Inspector in the CSXT Brooklyn Junction Yard discovered TILX 306200, a residue tank car of Liquefied Petroleum Gas, leaking from the B-End Liquid Line Valve. The car was isolated and the National Response Center, West Virginia DEP, and shipper were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report #2018-1108-00092). Specialized Professional Services, Inc., a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found both liquid line valves and the vapor line vale at least one quarter turn in the open position, and the B-End Liquid Line Valve secondary closure plug less than tool tight resulting in a release of hazardous materials. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Mr. Albert Daniel, phone 919-291-4832. Contractor personnel secured all valves and secondary closure. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 will be completed against Midland Manufacturing for this particular valve model.  Cause Code: 119 NARRI: 90

column168: An employee became suspicious of this package because the previous day the same shipper had sent what appeared to be this same package with a Lithium Battery Handling Label (Caution) but it was rejected and returned to the shipper for correction because the UN number was missing as a package marking to comply with FX 05d in the 2018 IATA DG regulations. However this package offered the next day did not have any DG markings or DG labels. I asked the DG specialist to have a manager open the package. Upon inspection of the contents it appeared to them to have some sort of cases with lithium batteries inside. They may be metal or ion. For purposes of reporting this undeclared DG I reported it as UN 3091, Lithium metal batteries contained in equipment. Upon later inspection of the photos it' s possible that these are batteries only in cases. The shipment was held pending FAA investigation.

column168: RESPONDER WAS CALLED FOR A LEAKING PACKAGE. DECISION TREE UTILIZED. UPON INSPECTION A LEAKING NON-REGULATED SUBSTANCE WAS DISCOVERED ALONG WITH 23 UNDECLARED AEROSOL CONTAINERS. NO MARKING OR LABELS ON OUTER CARTON.

AS PER STANDARD UNLOAD PROCEDURE, HAZMAT PACKAGE WAS NOT SENT ON TRADITIONAL BELT SYSTEM, BUT HELD UNTIL THE END OF THE DAY AND SENT ON THE IRREGULAR BELT. THE BOX SAFELY TRAVELED TO THE BULK LOADING AREA, WHERE EMPLOYEE INATTENTION LED TO THE HAZMAT REACHING THE END OF THE BELT. AS ADDITIONAL BOXES CAME BEHIND IT, THEY PUSHED THE BOX OFF THE BELT, WHERE IT TOOK A BAD FALL AND LANDED ON ITS SIDE. UPON LANDING THE CAP POPPED OFF AND THE CORROSIVE SOILED ALL FOUR BOTTLES

INITIAL EMAIL REPORT FROM OUR CARGO AGENT, ORIGINAL WAYBILL TEMPLATE, REVISED TEMPLATE, AND PROPER SHIPPER'S DECLARATION ARE INCLUDED WITH THIS REPORT. column168: While performing drum transfer on the yard, liquid was found to be on top of 2 drums from this  shipment. Also noted were drums that were bulging from over-pressurization. Contact was made to the shipper to inform them of the leaking drums and to see if they wanted us to perform the cleanup. They allowed us to perform the cleanup. Our crew mobilized to the trailer and donned appropriate PPE. The  drums were removed from the trailer and placed onto the ground. The lids were carefully removed to  relieve pressure. Once the pressure was normalized, the drums were placed into over-packed.

column168: On 11/13/2018 TILX 263753 was observed leaking material from the top of the car by NS personnel in the yard. Car was isolated and a NS contractor was notified to secure and clean material off of car. It was found that the 2" Vapor valve was in the open position and the 2" secondary closure cap was laying next to it. Because of this, under movement it caused product to leak out. The protective housing cover was in the close position and sealed with a MMT seal#. NS contractor cleaned the valve, closed the valve and put the cap on it. The exterior of the car was cleaned the following day.

column168: Field Service personnel delivered 4 over packed drums to the Romulus, MI Safety-Kleen facility. Prior to transport, free liquid was observed in one of the drums and a decision was made to solidify. Solidification at that time was accomplished with absorbent clay. Upon delivery, more free liquid was observed in the same drum. Solidification was again attempted. This time corn cob material was mistakenly used. The organic material reacted with the acid starting a fire in the drum. Personnel were immediately removed from the area and emergency services called. Upon arrival a single drum was found to be burning. This drum had been placed over secondary containment prior to the solidification effort. Emergency service personnel opted to allow the drum to self extinguish. Once cleared, Field Service personnel re-entered the building in proper PPE and supplied air. The remainder of the involved drum and material was repackaged into appropriate containers and set out for a 72 hour fire watch to ensure no re-ignition. At the completion of the required fire watch, the material was shipped to its original destination without further incident.
column169: All Field Service personnel have been re-trained as to proper solidification material choices. Organic stabilizers have been removed from the branch inventory.

column168: On 11/09/18, a UP train crew reported a strong odor and visible leak coming from the SGAX 1047 while at the BNSF/UP Interchange track 606 in Pittsburg, CA.  BNSF Hazmat responders inspected the car and found no evidence of leakage from the car.  On 11/10/18, the UP again reported that the car had a slight odor from the BOV threads on the car.  BNSF Hazmat and Dow Chemical responders responded and found the BOV threads to be intermittently releasing a small amount of vapor from the threads at the nozzle to the BOV Cap assembly.  Responders removed the cap to inspect.  The valve was intact and not leaking by, the threads were very dirty/greasy but the gasket was in good condition and in place.  The threads were cleaned and the cap assembly was re secured to the nozzle with a 36" pipe wrench.  All released vapor dissipated to atmosphere.  No environmental impacts were noted.
column169: Shipper should review maintenance procedures for this component on the cars.  It should be regularly inspected to be in good condition to travel leak free in transportation.(NAR:149)

column168: On 11/26/18 XPO terminal ULX experienced a Derakane Momentum™ 470-300 EPOXY VINYL ESTER RESIN release inside of a trailer. The drum containing the released material appeared to have rubbed against another piece of freight during transit and a small hole created. Due to the nature of the material, the leak was gradual, as the material began hardening quickly once outside of the drum, and fully hardened once on the floor of the trailer. The damaged drum was placed in an over-pack and the released material was scraped off of the floor and also containerized for disposal.

column168: On 11/17/2018 at 0706 CSX train Q64714 derailed at MP ANB 715.38 in Byromville, GA.   Tank cars UTLX 955767, UTLX 954209; CTCX 780629; and UTLX 955084 were involved in the derailment.  All four cars were loaded LPG tank cars shipped by Sunoco Partners Marketing & TE.   Shipper contact Edward Patterson (610-942-1924) Edward.Patterson@energytransfer.com was notified. The local fire department issued an evacuation of 14 apartment homes (approximately 30 residents) that were within the vicinity of the loaded LPG cars.  Once damage assessment and air monitoring were performed, the evacuation was lifted (approximately 1:30 pm on 11/17/18).  The power for the residents was  turned off due to power lines in vicinity of wrecking equipment, thus the residents did not return  to their houses until Sunday 11/18/18 around 2:30 pm when the power was restored.    This incident did not result in a release of hazardous materials from the four loaded LPG cars.
column169: No release - No NAR Code for this incident  No shipper information added to this incident, the PHMSA system would not allow CSX to submit this incident with shipper information. The system was forcing CSX to report a release when no release occurred. Multiple emails have been sent to PHMSA concerning this incident and report with no resolution. I have deleted the shipper information in order to submit this report

column168: On November 7, 2018, Dupre Logistics (11/7/18-LANCT) notified ERTS in regards to a E-87 Gasoline release. According to the caller, the driver of tractor (2929) cargo tank (22134) was offloading product into a UST when it over-filled. Approximately 20-gallons of product was released to the parking area. The caller has requested that a team be sent out to clean the release. 1138 ET, ERTS dispatched ES & H out of Lake Charles, LA. Contractor indicated that approximately 25-gallons of gasoline has been released to a 15 yard x 25 yard area of concrete. Contractor indicated that the gasoline is seeping through the contractor but there is no collection point. Contractor is going to place the absorbent boom around the concrete to contain the area.  Contractor has finished initial cleanup activities. Contractor has generated (4) 55-gallon poly drums of impacted absorbents so far. Boom placement around area will be picked up and area evaluated for any residual. As of right now, there is water standing around area in question. Contractor to return onsite Monday 11/12 to recover boom. Contractor generated (7) 55-gallon poly drums of impacted absorbent materials of waste to be taken off site for disposal.

column168: V1 was traveling eastbound on US Hwy 280. V1's Left front steer tire blew out unexpectedly. V1 pulled to the left, as V1 driver tried to regain control.  The load shifted and V1 fell onto its side.  V1 slid across the roadway and across the median crossover.  V1 continued sliding into the westbound lanes.  V2 was traveling westbound at the same time as V1 was directly in front of her path.  V2 driver applied her brakes hard but was unable to stop before hitting the cargo tank on the top (v1 on its side) that V1 was transporting.   V1 continued sliding crossing the westbound lanes and leaving the roadway.  V2 was pushed backwards after the impact, then coming to rest in the roadway.  V1's cargo tank was compromised and started leaking a hazardous material as it came to rest.  Witnesses and by standers called 911 immediately EMS, Fire and Rescue
column169: No recommendations for accident of this nature, equipment held up very well considering the force of the impact directly to the dome lid.  Dome lid did not fail or break open - it was bent and leaked from and around the gaskets.

column168: On November 27, 2018, at 0530 ET, XPO Logistics reported a 1-cup release of UN3109 "XGHENEX Peroxy X15" from one 55-gallon poly drum. It was stated that the drum fell off the pallet during dock operations and released to the dock floor. ERTS dispatched EcoFlo to conduct all onsite cleanup and over packing operations. Contractors arrived onsite at 0739 ET. AT 0837 ET, the contractor indicated that approximately 1-cup of product was released to a 2' x 3' area of the dock floor and (2) more small spots of approximately 1 square foot of the dock floor was impacted. the contractor indicated that the drum had a loose bung and contractor tightened it. At 0911 ET, the contractor finished cleanup activities. One 5-gallon poly pail of waste containing cleanup debris and PPE was generated. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: On 11/29/2018 at 1745 ET Christopher with XPO terminal UBI contacted ERTS concerning a spill of a small amount of battery acid to the top of a battery at the terminal. ETA of the response is 1930 ET. Chemtrec contacted report number: 2018112900306. No drains, soils, or waterways have been impacted by the release. Contractor arrived on site and neutralized the impacted area with soda ash. All waste was containerized and left at the facility for disposal.

column168: INVESTIGATION FINDINGS:  1. SHIPMENT WAS BUILT ON 12 NOV BY STAFF PERFORMING PRE-BUILD FOR THE FOLLOWING DAY'S FLIGHT. PRE-BUILD IS A REGULAR PROCESS THAT IS USED TO ADDRESS EXPORT VOLUMES AND KEEP THE WORK AREA ORGANIZED.  2. THE AGENT BUILDING THIS ULD DID NOT RECORD THE AWB NUMBER ON THE PALLET TAG/BUILD UP MANIFEST. THE OTHER SHIPMENTS ON THE ULD WERE CORRECTLY RECORDED BY THE AGENT.  3. ON THE MORNING OF 13 NOV, THE ULD WAS NETTED AND WEIGHED. CCTV OF THE SCALING ACTIVITY CLEARLY SHOW THIS SHIPMENT BUILT ON THE PMC.  4. THE BUILD UP MANIFEST WAS TRANSFERRED TO THE EXPORT OFFICE STAFF FOR MANIFESTING IN VOYAGER AND ALL OF THE OTHER SHIPMENTS ON ULD WERE MANIFESTED CORRECTLY. OFFICE STAFF HAD NO KNOWLEDGE OF THE UN-MANIFESTED PIECE BUILT ON THE ULD.
column169: CORRECTIVE ACTION: - AGENT ACTIONS HAVE BEEN ADDRESSED IN ACCORDANCE WITH DELTA'S PERFORMANCE DEVELOPMENT GUIDELINES.  PREVENTIVE ACTION: - CURTAIL PRACTICE OF PRE-BUILDING ANY DANGEROUS GOODS SHIPMENTS. DANGEROUS GOODS MAY ONLY BE BUILT ON THE DAY OF DEPARTURE.  - COMMUNICATION OF THIS CHANGE WILL BE MADE DURING DAILY BRIEFING AND WITH A READ AND SIGN DOCUMENT THAT WILL BE DISTRIBUTED THE WEEK OF 3DEC.

column168: Package was received at our shipping dock from a customer with a cockpit voice/data recorder(CVR) inside the package. The 90 day beacon on the CVR contains 1.75g lithium metal content so this was a lithium metal battery packaged in equipment shipment. Package had no markings that it was a dangerous goods/hazardous materials shipment. Our shipping department personnel unpackaged the unit and delivered the unit to our repair department. We notified the shipper they shipped a dangerous good without the proper labels and documentation and that they needed to remedy this in the future and that Universal Avionics was required to report the incident. There was no release.

column168: Package was received at our shipping dock from a customer with a cockpit voice/data recorder(CVR) inside the package. Package did have a 3091 lithium metal battery label but not the class 9 label it requires. The package also didn't have a dangerous goods declaration. Our shipping department personnel unpackaged the unit and delivered the unit to our repair department. We notified the shipper they shipped a dangerous good without the proper labels and documentation and that they needed to remedy this in the future and that Universal Avionics was required to report the incident. There was no release.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: At approximately 18:10 PST on 11/15/18, the JRSX 1043 was found with a small wet stain on the tank car shell.  Local forces isolated the car and made notifications.  A BNSF approved contractor was dispatched and inspected the car.  It was noted that there was phosphoric acid liquid near and around the external PRV seal area.  External inspection revealed that the valve appeared to be intact with no obvious signs of an issue on the outer part of the valve or valve seat.  Pressure was checked in the car and it was negligent, responders also inspected for outage and noted adequate outage in the car.  The acid was neutralized and car cleaned.  UTLX mobile repair later removed the PRV to rebuild the valve and reinstall at a later to be determined date.  It is unknown at time of reporting as to the root cause of failure for the valve.
column169: Advised shipper/car owner to have a root cause analysis performed on the PRV during rebuilding.(NAR:422)

column168: Driver Rogers was traveling north on highway 550 in CO. Just south of Silverton, CO the driver lost control of the tractor/ trailer combination and left the highway to the left causing the vehicle to overturn. The tractor disconnected from the trailer. Product leaked from a connection on top of the trailer where a vapor return valve connected to a 3" pipe nipple. When the state hazmat officer arrived work was performed to minimize the leak. When the ER contractor arrived spill containment was established to contain the leaking material.   The next day a recovery trailer arrived and the product in the overturned cargo tank was pumped into the recovery cargo tank trailer.   At the time of this report the recovered product is waiting to be tested for purity for the shipper to determine if they wil accept the material. No determination has been made to the amount of product that was not recovered. Product lost amounts in this report and all cost amounts are estimated.

column14: CSX New Castle Yard MP BG 61
column168: On 11/12/2018, at 1628 hours, personnel in the CSXT New Castle Yard discovered GBRX 700614, a loaded tank car of Petroleum Crude Oil, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the National Response Center, Pennsylvania Department of Environmental Protection, and shipper were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report #2018-1112-00228). Specialized Professional Services, Inc., a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the vapor line valve in the open position and the secondary closure cap not secured in accordance with 49 CFR 173.31. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Mr. Nate Wylie, phone 972-735-3369. Contractor personnel closed the valve, installed the secondary closure, and removed all spilled material. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.  Cause Code: 380 NARRI: 80

column168: On 11/23/2018, at 1115 hours, personnel in the CSXT Parsons Yard discovered UTLX 200556, a loaded tank car of Hydrogen Peroxide, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, National Response Center, and Ohio EPA were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report #2018-1123-00039). SUNPRO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found a release of lading from the liquid eduction line at the flanged connection below the valve due to a pinched gasket. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, Mr. Ralph Mikida, phone 267-422-2405. Contractor personnel covered the external valve with polypropylene sheeting and removed all spilled material from the car. The valve will require repair from an AAR approved Mobile Repair Unit; to replace the damaged gasket and requalification. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 will be completed.  Cause Code: 292 NARRI: 100

column168: The leaking container was discover by a Veolia 10-day intransit facility employee while preparing an outbound load. The leak was identified by white whispy fumes coming form near the base of a group of drums.  Upon further investigation, the employee moved the drum and found a small amount of material on the floor of the trailer.  Tipping the drum on its side showed that the source of the material on the trailer floor and the white whisps was a small hole on the bottom of the drum.  The employee evacuated the immediate area and notified his immediate supervisor.  Representatives of the Veolia Safety Department and Reactive Chemicals Group responded to a call for assistance from the supervisor.  A review of a the packing slip summary indicated that the contents of the drum was metal chloride clean up debris.  Given the small amount of material released (<25 mL debris, <5 mL metal chloride), the favorable conditions present at  the spill location (well-ventilated), and the employee expertise on hand, the following steps were used to manage the  incident safely, quickly, and efficiently: additional PPE was donned, a salvage drum was secured, absorbent material  was applied to all effected areas and to the bottom of the salvage container, the leaking drum was double-bagged and  placed into the salvage container, the spill clean-up debris (<5 lbs) was added to the salvage drum, and the salvage drum  was closed per manufacturer's specifications/closure instructions. In total, the response activities lasted <45 minutes.  To ensure safe and expedited transportation and material management, the transporter (Veolia driver) was fully informed  of the situation (minimal hazard and risk post-response), the drum was immediately transported to the disposal facility  (with intentional placement at the back end to the trailer, and the disposal facility was fully notified of the situation to  ensure safe and expedited management upon receipt.
column169: Post-incident, an Incident Investigation and a Root Cause Analysis were conducted and yielded the  following actions item: contact a generator representative to discuss the incident causes & and  preventative measures to prevent recurrence.  In that the cause for the incident was determined  to be an incompatibility between the packaging and it's contents, the incident would have been  prevented had the shipper followed current hazardous materials transportation regulations.

column168: During routine facility unloading operations, a forklift operator punctured a container releasing some of its contents.  An onsite, trained, emergency response team was immediately dispatched to assist. In appropriate personal protective equipment, verified through the internal health and safety department, the response team was successful in over packing the compromised container and in cleaning the transport trailer. No water ways, storm drains, land or soil were impacted as a result of this release. A spill notification report was made to the Washington State Department of Ecology and state report number 685437 was generated.
column169: The forklift operator was removed from duty and thoroughly retrained on all forklift responsibility. An emphasis was placed on situational awareness and taking ones time to stay focused on the tasks at hand.

column168: On November 21, 2018 at approximately 1050 hours, a Mechanical Inspector at Conrail's Morrisville  Yard in Morrisville, Pennsylvania, reported that UTLX 666908, a loaded tank car of UN 2303,  Isopropenylbenzene was leaking from the top of the tank car. The tank car was isolated and the  shipper Advansix Inc. was notified via Chemtrec, report # 2018-11-21-00114. Conrail Hazardous Material  Manager, Allen Richter along with Hepaco, a Conrail response contractor, were dispatched to the  Morrisville Yard and found a slosh leak had occurred from the manway area of the tank car. Upon further  inspection it was found that five of the six manway securement bolts were improperly secured thus causing  the leak. The manway was opened to inspect the gasket which was found in proper condition and all six  manway securement bolts were tightened appropriately. The tank car was wiped down and then released back  into transportation. The Shipper representative, Larry Buffey Jr. (973) 526-1633 was informed of the situation  found.  Cause Code: 200 NARRI: 5X(5+1+0)X(2+0) = 60

column168: FORKLIFT OPERATOR WAS MOVING 9/ 275-GALLON TOTES OF SPENT PICKLE LIQUOR WASTE (NITRIC ACID/HYDROCHLORIC ACID MIXTURE - REFER TO DOCUMENT #1) FROM 53' VAN TRAILER POSITIONED AT DOCK A INTO 8016 BOX VAN STRAIGHT TRUCK AT DOCK B "(REFER TO DIAGRAM #1). TWO TOTES OF WASTE WERE STAGED SIDE BY SIDE IN 8016 BOX VAN (TOTE #1 & #2), WHEN TOTE #3 WAS LOADED AND PLACED IN FRONT OF TOTE #2, TOTE #2 WAS PUNCTURED BY FORKS THAT WERE EXTENDED PAST TOTE #3. PICTURE #1 SHOWS PUNCTURED TOTE #2. OPERATOR IMMEDIATELY NOTICED CONTENTS OF TOTES SPILLING FROM PUNCTURES ON TOTE #2, SO PICKED TOTE #3 AND REMOVED IT FROM 8016 BOX VAN ONTO SPILL CONTAINMENT SO THAT IT COULD BE CONTAINED. PICTURE #2 SHOWS WERE SPILL INSIDE BOX VAN WAS SPILLED. OPERATOR THEN WENT INSIDE THE OFFICE AND ASKED FOR ASSISTANCE TO CLEAN UP SPILL MATERIAL THAT HAD LEAKED THROUGH THE VAN FLOOR ONTO PARKING LOT BELOW.BASED ON MATERIAL REMAINING IN TOTE AND RECOVERED FROM SPILL CONTAINMENT, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT BETWEEN 30-35 GALLONS OF MATERIAL HAD SPILLED. A CREW OF 40-HOUR HAZWOPER TRAINED RESPONDERS USED ABSORBENT BOOM, PADS, RAGS, AND VERMICULITE TO ABSORB THE SPILLED MATERIAL IN THE BOX VAN, PARKING LOT AND WAREHOUSE FLOOR. SPILL WAS CONTAINED UNDERNEATH THE BOX VAN AND DID NOT REACH ANY SOIL OR WATERWAYS. THE WASTE THAT CAPTURED IN SPILL CONTAINMENT WAS TRANSFERRED INTO 7/55-GALLON POLY CLOSED TOP DRUMS (REFER TO PICTURE #3), LABELED AND PLACED IN 10-DAY STORAGE AREA. THE ABSORBENTS WERE PLACED INTO 55-GALLON DRUMS USED TO CLEAN UP LIQUIDS WERE PLACED IN DRUMS (REFER TO PICTURE #4-7). THE PUNCTURED TOTE WAS CUT UP AND PLACED IN A CUBIC YARD BOX. CREW LAID OUT VISQUEEN DIRECTLY IN FRONT OF TRUCK AND PULLED 8016 BOX VAN ONTO VISQUEEN. HOT WATER PRESSURE WASHER WAS USED TO DECONTAMINATED TIRES AND TRUCK. RINSATES WERE COLLECTED INTO 55-GALLON DRUM. VISQUEEN WAS DISPOSED OF IN LABELED CUBIC YARD BOX WITH TOTE PIECES. CREW THEN PRESSURE WASHED IMPACTED PARKING LOT WITH HOT WATER PRESSURE WASHER COLLECTING THE RINSATES INTO A 55-GALLON DRUM (REFER TO PICTURES #8-#11). THE SPILL BOOM SURROUNDING THE BOX VAN/IMPACTED PARKING LOT AREA WAS THEN REMOVED AND PLACED INTO 55-GALLON DRUMS FOR DISPOSAL. THE SPILL CONTAINMENT IN WAREHOUSE WAS ALSO PRESSURE WASHED CLEAN AND THE RINSATES COMBINED WITH OTHER RINSATES INTO DRUM. ALL DRUMS WERE LABELED AND PLACED IN WASTE STORAGE AREA. THE 8 INTACT TOTES AND 7/55-GALLON DRUMS PF PICKLE LIQUOR WERE DELIVERED TO DESTINATION (REFER TO DOCUMENT #2). WASTE GENERATED FROM SPILL CLEANUP WAS PROFILED (REFER TO DOCUMENT #3 & #4 INTO HERITAGE'S INDIANAPOLIS TREATMENT FACILITY AND SHIPPED FOR DISPOSAL ON 12-7-18 ( REFER TO DOCUMENT #5).

column168: when driver arrived at a prior stop in Townville, SC to make home delivery he was on very steep incline the road had approx. 45 degree incline and when he removed the load bar to get the package to actually be delivered the 2 IBC containers behind it started sliding and fell off back of trailer onto  the street. The top on one of the IBC's poped open and approx 150 lbs of material leaked out. The other IBC appeared to be okay, but some small leakage may have come from the bottom of IBC. As soon as this happend our driver reported to local dispatcher and he then called ABF safety and security ho tline to report. Haz mat clean up team was contracted to clean up. Exposed material was contained in 55 gallon drum and the IBC's were loaded back on ABF trailer and taken back to local service center. Waiting on disposition of disposal of contaiminated material and sent the 2 IBC's to consignee on 11/21 so they can inspect.
column169: In future loader/checker of any haz material should secure actual shipment independently and not rely on other freight to block and brace. A load bar was utilized in front of IBC's and then another load bar was used behind them, but with two other shipments in-between. I would also note that on the bottom feet of IBC's a (plastic-nylon type foot) applies to each of the 4 legs, this makes the IBC's slide easily and with any type incline would allow them to move fairly easy.  I will be taking disciplinary/coaching action on the loader/checker who loaded the shipment on route trailer as this is so mething we cover in all safety meetings.

Original comments:  DAMAGED UPON ARRIVAL TO STATION. AFTER FURTHER INVESTIGATION BY QA, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE LEAKING HAZMAT WAS CAUSED BY A LOOSE CAP/CLOSURE ON ONE OF HTE 1 GALLON PLASTIC JUGS. WHILE HANDLING THE PACKAGE, A PACKAGE HANDLER SPILLED SOME OF THE HAZMAT ON THEIR SKIN. THE LIQUID WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH AMPHOMAG. A FOLLOW-UP WITH THE PACKAGE HANDLER WAS CONDUCTED BEFORE THE END OF THE PRE-LOAD SORT AND THE FOLLOWING DAY. THE PACKAGE HANDLER REPORTED NO FURTHER ISSUES WHERE THE HAZMAT CONTACTED THEIR SKIN. DURATION OF RELEASE WAS LESS THAN 30 MINUTES. CAPS/CLOSURES OF PLASTIC JUGS SHOULD HAVE BEEN TIGHTENED AND SECURE FOR TRANSPORT TO PREVENT SPILLING. PACKAGE HANDLERS ALSO SHOULD HAVE FOLLOWED DIRECTIONAL ARROWS. SDS IS FOR ZEP FS FORMULA 4089 4-1 GALLON.  New Comments:

column168: At 1859T, ERTS was notified by XPO Logistics of a spill that occurred at a customer's location (Arrow Materials Handling Products - 16000 West 108th Lenexa, KS 66219) at 1840 ET. At 1917 ET the caller noticed the freight was leaking once at the customer's location from (1) 55-gallon steel drum of UN1866 Resin to the tail of the floor of trailer #4416824. It was reported that the customer refused the freight. At 2035 ET, Environmental Works (EW) personnel arrived on site at the customer's location and confirmed there were (2) 55-gallon steel drums of the HAP 30 White material still on the trailer but only one was damaged. The damaged drum was dented towards the bottom and released an estimated 1/2 a cup of material to the trailer floor. EW placed granular absorbents on the area to get it cleaned. The second drum has some type of material at the bottom weld of the drum and was also rejected by the customer. Due to the integrity of both containers being questionable, ERTS instructed EW to overpack both containers and place the original labels back on the truck. The truck then moved over to the XPO XKC terminal where both drum overpacks were off loaded and placed into the waste area.

At 0747 ET, XPO Logistics contacted ERTS to report a 0.5-gallon release of UN1824 Sodium Hydroxide solution to the trailer and dock floor in an area measuring 3' x 40'  due to a forklift puncture. At 1024 ET, contractors arrived onsite and found that oil dry had already been placed down to contain the release. The absorbents were collected and placed into a 55-gallon poly drum. The damaged drum was placed into an 85-gallon poly drum. All waste was staged in the terminals waste area for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: Derailment cause by a break in the track, on a pull back lead, at UPRR North Platte Bailey Yard. While pulling cars out of the west bowl tracks the break in the rail caused 14 cars to derail. 9 cars were on their side and one tank car GATX 33058 was leaking from the liquid line flange. Upon investigation it was determined that the leak was cause by the torque on the liquid line flange while the car was on its side. The bolts on the flange were tightened until the leak ceased. Approximately 5 gallons of ethanol was released onto the ground.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 0145 HOURS ON 15 NOVEMBER 2018 A RIO EXPRESS CORP. DRIVER WAS TRANSPORTING A PARTIAL LOAD OF USED ANTIFREEZE (ETHYLENE GLYCOL) APPROXIMATELY 5288 GALLONS ON A TANKER THAT HOLDS 9400 GALLONS. THE DRIVER WAS HEADING SOUTHBOUND ON 710 FREEWAY AT INTERSTATE 5 BRIDGE, THE SECTION OF THE FREEWAY IS BEING GRADED AND HAS A SLOPE, THIS CAUSE THE TRUCK TO SHIFT  TO THE LEFT. THE DRIVER MADE AN ATTEMPT TO CORRECT THE SHIFT BY PULLING SLIGHTLY TO THE RIGHT TO AVOID VEHICLES ON HIS LEFT. THE ABRUPT MANEUVER CAUSED THE PARTIAL LOAD TO CAUSE TO SWAY THE TANKER DRAMATICALLY TO WHERE IT FORCED IT TO ROLL OVER ON ITS RIGHT SIDE, DRAGGING APPROXIMATELY 40 FT. THE TANKER HIT THE CENTER DIVIDER WHICH PUNCTURED THE TRAILER CREATING THE LEAKAGE. THE DRIVER CALLED 911 EMERGENCY AT 0148 TO NOTIFY THEM OF THE INCIDENT AND TO INITIATE SPILL RESPONSE. PER DEPUTY HEALTH OFFICER/HAZMAT SPECIALIST GERHARD TRIPPEL, APPROXIMATELY 160 GALLONS OF MATERIAL SPILLED INTO THE DRAIN, IT DID NOT ENTER THE WATER WAY. HAZMAT COMPANY OCEAN BLUE DID ALL CLEAN-UP INCLUDING STEAM PRESSURE. LIQUIDS MATERIALS WHERE CLEANED UP AND HANDLED BY DEMMENO-KERDOON APPROXIMATELY 15 DRUMS AND SOLIDS MATERIALS WAS HANDLED BY CROSBY & OVERTON AND TAKEN TO THE LONG BEACH FACILITY FOR TREATMENT.
column169: POST INCIDENT, THE DRIVER WAS REMINDED OF THE IMPORTANCE OF SAFE DRIVING PRACTICES THROUGH RE-TRAINING, ESPECIALLY WHILE DRIVING WITH THE A PARTIAL LOAD WHICH REQUIRE ADDITIONAL ATTENTION. THE TANKER AND THE TRUCK WHERE TAKEN TO THE TOW YARD WHERE THE INSURANCE PROVIDER WILL DECIDE ON THE REPAIRS.

column168: While preparing to offload into storage tanker, the driver prepared his lines, checked his valves and  at the direction of the facility operator began to offload.  Once the driver started to pump, his hose  blew off.  Driver immediately shown down his pump stopping the flow.  Internal spill team responded and cleaned the area.  All contaminated soil and cleanup materials  was placed in a drum for transport without further incident.  The vehicles were placed out of service pending inspection.  Upon investigation we learned the facility operator did not open the valves on his tank in order to  receive the product.
column169: While the driver fount not to be at fault, we have implemented procedures that require the receiving operator to be present to prepare his tank.  Additionally, the facility is to draw up and SOP  speaking to that; an operator from the facility must be present while loading / offloading.

On November 24, 2018, at 0218 ET, ERTS was contacted by Schneider Bulk about a tanker cargo release. It was reported that due to a tanker puncture approximately 490-gallons of hazardous UN2582 Ferric Chloride released from a Schneider Bulk tanker. The caller stated that the released product was contained to a gravel area on the Quala Tank Wash facility. The caller stated that the tanker as completely empty. Cleanup contractor was requested for cleaning the impacted area.  At 0415 ET, Hepaco personnel arrived onsite  0430 ET, Hepaco personnel located the release and confirmed 490 gallons of Ferric Chloride released onto the gravel lot, into soil, and into a drainage ditch that lead to the Ohio River. Hepaco confirmed the impacted area was an 8' x 660' area. Soda ash was used as neutralizer on the impacted area and the top layer of the gravel was scraped up. Hepaco used an excavator and rolloff to collect the waste. Tanker was confirmed to not be leaking anymore. At 0500 ET, Oil dry was placed into the drainage ditch to prevent further mitigation. At 0515 ET, the impacted gravel was neutralized with soda ash. At 0849 ET, contractor scraped off all contaminated dirt. All of the impacted water was neutralized (about a 5ftx8ft area). 1238 ET, contractor generated 3 roll off boxes of waste that were left onsite.  On November 28, 2018, at 0900 ET, Hepaco arrived back onsite. The remaining gravel was scraped up and placed into roll off boxes On November 29, 2018, at 0730 ET, contractors arrived onsite to complete the backfill of the gravel lot. On November 30, 2018, at 0730 ET, Hepaco arrived onsite and removed the roll offs for disposal. This incident is still ongoing and remediation is pending for the wetlands impacted. Per the DEP the advised that some product bypassed the area where the booms were and ran through a ditch towards the creek but stopped short by 50-100 feet. He advised he wants to see remediation there as well. Plans to excavate the area are in progress at this time.

column168: On 11/27/2018 at 10:45am, a Lykins Oil Company (Lykins) driver delivered home heating oil to a customer at 555 Knoxville Road, Dry Ridge, KY 41035. The customer has a 275 gallon basement tank, the driver was outside filling the tank while listening for air. When he felt that it was filled more than he thought was correct, he stopped to check the meter, it noted 281.5 gallons. The driver then alerted the customer and they went inside the customers home to check the tank in the basement and it had overfilled. The tank gauge and cap were off and were sitting on top of the tank, which is why the air could not be heard while it was being filled. Lykins was immediately contacted by the driver and made aware of the spill. The Director of Safety, Environmental, and Maintenance contacted the National Response Center (NRC# 1231407), The Kentucky EPA (EPA#20186233), and Environmental Management Specialists, Inc. on 11/27/2018 and met their representatives at the spill location. They assessed the spill and any property damage and environmental concerns then concluded that the family was to stay in a hotel while the basement was cleaned up. The basement is being remodeled, everything that was damaged has been removed and will be replaced. The basement remodeling is ongoing.
column169: In our spring safety meetings we will be emphasizing the importance of taking your time and being overly cautious when filling tanks. We want to make sure that the drivers know they can always stop the flow,check the meter, and then continue the flow again if they are unsure of how full the tank is. We will also be reminding our customers the importance of tank maintenance and how it can effect many aspects of the unloading process.

Package was received at our shipping dock from a customer with a cockpit voice/data recorder(CVR) inside the package. The 90 day beacon on the CVR contains 1.75g lithium metal content so this was a lithium metal battery packaged in equipment shipment. Package had no markings that it was a dangerous goods/hazardous materials shipment. Our shipping department personnel unpackaged the unit and delivered the unit to our repair department. We notified the shipper they shipped a dangerous good without the proper labels and documentation and that they needed to remedy this in the future and that Universal Avionics was required to report the incident. There was no release.
column169: Our personnel have received training on recognizing hazardous materials arriving at our dock with issues and to notify management where an incident occurs. We provided additional training to recognize when a hazardous material arrives without the appropriate markings or documentation and no release and to immediately report it to management so we can capture all the appropriate information in order to report the incident. We have also notified customers and dealers through newsletters, a notice on our customer website and a service bulletin about reshipping this particular product for repairs and the need to ship as dangerous goods/hazardous material.

column168: Original comments:  While a package handler was loading the trailer, they noticed a wet/leaking package and informed their manager.  The manager quickly informed QA of the situation they had in their area.  QA grabbed a red tote, lined it with a clear hazmat bag and grabbed loose absorb.  They rushed over to the area to investigate the situation.  Upon arrival, they noticed the package in question was flammable liquid and placed it in the tote.  QA cleaned up the area with the loose absorb and brought the package back to QA placing it in the hazmat processing cage.  New Comments:

Driver was conducting a right-hand turn when the rear trailer tires went into the culvert. This caused the trailer and truck to roll onto its right side. Upon landing, the trailer was punctured by a 6" pipe fence post creating a 16" hole in the shell of the trailer. This caused a release of the trailer's load of 190 bbls of Crude Oil. Clean up began immediately with a vacuum truck and 171 bbls were recovered from the scene. The remaining 19.12 bbls was removed through remediation.

column168: It was confirmed that, due to a load shift, (1) 55- gallon poly drum released approximately 25 gallons of UN3264 corrosive liquid DART 158 onto a 10' x 5' area of the trailer floor and a 5' x 5' area of the gravel  on the exit ramp shoulder.  The Contractor utilized soda sh to neutralize the release.  The damaged drum was over-packed into a 95-gallon poly drum.  The impacted absorbents were placed into (2) 55-gallon poly drums. All generated waste was taken offsite for disposal.
column198: EMERGENCY RESPONSE AND TRAINING SOLUTIONS, INCORPORATED

column168: On November 28, 2018, at 1024 ET, M.C. Tank Transport called ERTS to report a release of UN2218 Acrylic Acid from a Cargo Tank. It was stated that while a mechanic was drilling a hole on the tank, he pierced the tank causing a release of approximately 50-gallons to the soil. ERTS dispatched Hepaco to the site to conduct cleanup and remediation activities. At 1049 ET, contractors arrived onsite. The release was secured at 1151 ET.  at 1505 ET, the area of soil impacted was measured to be approximately 10' x 10'. 30-gallons had been recovered from the tank and a confirmed 20-gallons released to the ground. At 1615 ET, contractors completed cleanup for the day and generated two 30-gallon poly drums of solid waste and one 30-gallon poly drum of Acrylic Acid in liquid form. On November 29, 2018, Hepaco returned to the site to complete the tank transfer. and then removed the impacted jacket on December 6, 2018. The outer jacket and insulation from the tanks were placed into a cubic yard box. All work was completed and Hepaco departed site.

column168: Driver struck a privately owned light pole as he entered a Circle K location in Fayetteville, NC.  The result was damage to the pole and our number 4 and 5 wet lines. This caused a release of  approximately 18-20 gals of RUL product onto the soil and pavement. Fayetteville PD, FD and  the HAZMAT Rapid Response Teams responded. Selma Shop Foreman and the FSM also responded  to the scene. Wrecker service had to be called to move the trailer off of the pole without causing more damage. They also assisted with getting the compartments with damaged lines unloaded. All product was delivered to the intended location. The driver did a good job of containing the release, so there was no impact to storm water systems  or waterways.

column168: Car was scheduled to be moved to Arkema, Calvert City, KY.  The car was bad ordered during inspection for unrelated issue.  While in the shop undergoing repairs the car began venting.  Arkema was notified and called E3, (Enhanced Emergency and Environmental Services) to make necessary repairs.  E3 tightened valve which stopped venting.  Our Environmental contractor 5H was also called and stated in their report "a Reportable Quantity (RQ) never occurred."  This was a residue car.

column169: DRIVING TRAINING TO EMPHASIZE PROPER PRETRIPS, AND INATTENTIVE OPERATION.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 5:00 P.M. CST ON THURSDAY NOVEMBER 15, 2018, OUR COMPANY WAS NOTIFIED BY A MOTORIST THAT ONE OF OUR TRAILERS WAS SPILLING A LIQUID OUT THE BACK DOOR OF THE TRAILER. BASED ON THE VEHICLE IDENTIFICATION NUMBERS GIVEN, OUR DISPATCH RECORDS INDICATED THAT THE DRIVER WAS ON NORTHBOUND INTERSTATE 41, ABOUT 15 MILES NORTH OF MILWAUKEE, WISCONSIN. OUR DRIVER WAS THEN CONTACTED BY OUR 2ND SHIFT OPERATIONS MANAGER AND INFORMED OF THE SPILL. THE DRIVER THEN ENTERED THE FIRST EXIT RAMP AVAILABLE, WHICH WAS THE EXIT RAMP AT THE HIGHWAY 144 EXIT.  A SPILL RESPONSE AGENCY (SPILL CENTER, HUDSON, MA) WAS NOTIFIED BY OUR 2ND SHIFT OPERATIONS MANAGER TO EXPEDITE THE LOCATING OF A SPILL RESPONSE CONTRACTOR THAT COULD GET TO THE SPILL LOCATION. VEOLIA NORTH AMERICA, GERMANTOWN, WI WAS CONTRACTED TO DO THE REMEDIATION AT THE SCENE.  VEOLIA DISCOVERED THAT A RATCHET OR BUCKLE FROM A STRAP HAD BROKEN OFF ONE OF THE RAILS FROM THE WALL WITH SUCH FORCE THAT IT PUNCTURED THE TOP SIDE CORNER OF THE WHITE PLASTIC BOTTLE OF THE IBC. THE PUNCTURE RESULTED IN A HALF DOLLAR SIZE OPENING IN THE PLASTIC WALL OF THE IBC.  THE DRIVER HAD PUT FOUR IBC'S INSIDE OF THE VERY BACK OF THE TRAILER. HE PLACED ONE STRAP BEHIND THE IBC'S (WALL TO WALL), AND ANOTHER STRAP IN FRONT OF THE FOUR IBC'S, ALSO WALL TO WALL. WE BELIEVE THE FRONT STRAP BROKE LOOSE WITH A LOT FORCE, HITTING THE CORNER OF THE IBC, RIPPING RIGHT THROUGH THE PLASTIC.  VEOLIA APPLIED HUNDREDS OF POUNDS OF ABSORBENTS TO THE INSIDE OF THE TRAILER AND THEN TRANSFERRED ALL THE CORROSIVE LIQUID FROM THE PUNCTURED IBC TO A NEW EMPTY IBC. THE ESTIMATED DURATION OF THE REMEDIATION FROM VEOLIA WAS APPROXIMATELY 9:45 P.M. TO 11:35 P.M., JUST UNDER TWO HOURS.
column169: WE BELIEVE THE CAUSE OF THIS IBC PUNCTURE WAS THE RESULT OF THE DRIVER FAILING TO APPLY STRAPS TO THE IBC'S PROPERLY. OUR INVESTIGATION INDICATES THAT HAD THE DRIVER STRAPPED TWO EACH OF THESE FOUR IBCS SECURELY TO EACH SIDEWALL, THIS EVENT WOULD NOT HAVE OCCURRED. STRAPPING THE FOUR TOTES WITH ONE STRAP IN FRONT AND ONE IN BACK CREATED TO MUCH SLACK, WHICH IN TURN PUT TOO MUCH PRESSURE ON THE RATCHETS AND RAIL CLIPS. ADDITIONAL TRAINING INFORMATION ON PROPER IBC SECUREMENT HAS AND IS BEING FORWARDED TO BOTH OUR DOCK PERSONNEL AND OUR DRIVERS THROUGH A VISUAL PRESENTATION IN OUR DRIVERS ROOM TELEVISION DISPLAY AND THROUGH OUR THREE COMPANY DRIVER TRAINERS.
column172: Composite, with a rigid plastic inner receptacle for liquids and a steel outer packaging

column168: ON 11-30-2018 AT THE INTERSECTION OF GLEN RD, AN CLEVELAND SCHOOL RD. IN GARNER, NC A PASSENGER VEHICLE PULLED OUT IN FRONT OF AN AGUA NORTH CARDINAL VEHICLE, CAUSING A COLLISION. THE AGUA VEHICLE WAS A DOT REGISTERED VEHICLE CARRYING SMALL QUANTITIES OF OF SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTION FOR A WELL WATER SYSTEM IN AND AROUND GARNER NORTH CAROLINE. THE 45 MPH IMPACT CAUSED 3-5 GALLONS OF SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTION TO REACH THE GROUND. THE SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTION WAS TREATED BY CHASE ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES OF NORTH CAROLINA. THE PASSENGER VEHICLE THAT STRUCK THE AGUA NORTH CAROLINA VEHICLE WAS CITED FOR FAILURE TO YIELD.

column168: OUR EMPLOYEE WAS APPLYING ANHYDROUS AMMONIA WHEN THE HITCH PIN THAT CONNECTED THE ANHYDROUS AMMONIA NURSE TANK TO THE ANHYDROUS BAR SNAPPED IN HALF.  AFTER THE PIN SNAPPED, THE NURSE TANK WAS NO LONGER CONNECTED TO THE ANHYDROUS BAR. THE 2 WITHDRAWAL HOSES THAT TRANSFER THE ANHYDROUS AMMONIA FROM THE NURSE TANK TO THE ANHYDROUS AMMONIA BAR EACH GO INTO THEIR OWN SAFETY QUICK RELEASE COUPLER.  THESE SAFETY COUPLERS ARE DESIGNED TO ALLOW THE WITHDRAWAL HOSES TO BE PULLED OUT AT AROUND 400 TO 500 POUNDS OF FORCE. ONCE THEY ARE PULLED OUT, A QUICK RELEASE VALVE CLOSES TO KEEP ANY ANHYDROUS AMMONIA FROM BEING RELEASED.  FOR REASONS UNKNOWN, THE SAFETY QUICK RELEASE COUPLERS DID NOT PULL FREE AT THE REQUIRED PULL FORCE. IT TOOK A MUCH GREATER FORCE TO PULL THEM FREE. ONCE THEY BOTH PULLED FREE, THE WITHDRAWAL HOSES WERE STRETCHED AND WHEN THEY RELEASED, THE QUICK COUPLER ENDS SHOT BACK INTO THE NURSE TANK.  WITHDRAWAL HOSE A, DID NOT GET DAMAGED AFTER STRIKING THE NURSE TANK.  THE 1/4' BLEEDER VALVE ON WITHDRAWAL HOSE B WAS SNAPPED OFF AFTER STRIKING THE NURSE TANK.  THE FLOW OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA OUT OF THE BLEEDER VALVE HOLE WAS NOT GREAT ENOUGH TO TRIGGER THE EXCESS FLOW VALVE TO CLOSE.  THE FARMWARD EMPLOYEE MOVED HIS TRACTOR UPWIND AND THEN CALLED HIS MANAGER.  THE MANAGER CALLED ME, AARON GUGGISBERG.  I CALLED, IN ORDER, 911 (MORGAN FIRE DEPARTMENT), MN DUTY OFFICER (REPORT #178892) AND NRC.  THE MORGAN FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS ABLE TO CONTROL THE RELEASE OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA WITH WATER AND CLOSE THE WITHDRAWAL VALVE ON THE NURSE TANK.
column169: THE SAFETY QUICK RELEASE COUPLER WAS SENT TO THE MANUFACTURER (CONTINENTAL NH3) TO BE EXAMINED TO SEE IF A CAUSE OF FAILURE COULD BE DETERMINED.  AS OF 02/21/2019, FARMWARD COOP HAS NOT RECEIVED NOTIFICATION FROM CONTINENTAL NH3 ON WHETHER A FAILURE CAUSE HAD BEEN DETERMINED.

column168: The insured's trailer was struck by a locomotive, causing damage to the tractor trailer and locomotive, as well as a release of liquid asphalt (tar) onto the road, Trinity Railway Express (TRE) track and its ballast, soil, a storm drain and the Dallas Area Rapid Transit (DART) locomotive and railcar.  Lone Star HazMat Response (Lone Star) responded and used sand to contain the flow of the hot liquid asphalt (tar) and to recover it as it cooled. The train tracks were scraped with a skid steer so that rail traffic could continue. The locomotive and commuter railcars were removed by another engine to an alternate track and Lone Star placed thick plastic sheeting around all ends to contain any possible tar runoff. Sand was mixed into the cooling tar and collected into a roll-off container. Tar on the ground was excavated into three additional roll-off containers for disposal.  Lone Star returned to the site on November 26, 2018 to perform two separate activities: A) begin completion of recovering all tar from the impact site; and B) clean tar from the railcar which was directly behind the locomotive. (NOTE: The locomotive was scheduled to be transported to Canada for repairs, which is estimated to take several more months; therefore, the locomotive damages are under a separate claim). November 26, 2018:   A) Lone Star excavated the tar-contaminated gravel below the railroad tracks (ballast) and loaded it into a dump truck for disposal. A specialty non-hazardous, tar­removing chemical compound (Bess Solution) was delivered.in a 375-gallon tote and sprayed on the sides of the railroad tracks. A heated pressure washer with surfactant was then used to clean the tracks. The tar-contaminated ballast and contaminated soil from this process was excavated into one roll-off container for disposal. · B) The railcar was moved to a TRE train shop. Lone Star placed plastic underneath · and around the railcar to contain the runoff from the cleaning process. Lone Star personnel used safety harnesses and cables while on a scissor lift for the cleaning of this double-decker commuter railcar. Bess Solution was applied to the railcar and a heated pressure washer with surfactant was used to clean the railcar. The runoff from this process was channeled to a shop drain, which leads to an isolated, underground oil/water separator. This process continued on November 27, 28, 29, 30, 2018, and December 3,4,5, and 7, 2018.  November 27 and 28, 2018:  A) Lone Star excavated contaminated ballast underneath the railroad tracks with hand tools, to prevent potential damage of the tracks by heavy equipment. Ballast removed from below the tracks was then placed into two dump trucks by an excavator. Twenty-Four (24) cubic yards of new ballast was used to replace the excavated ballast.  November 29, 2018:   A) Lone Star used a heated pressure washer with a surfactant to clean the metal barriers and crossing arms on both sides of the track. column168: THE DRIVER PULLED INTO THE LOCATION AND POSITIONED THE TRACTOR NEAR THE UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK DROPS. HE EXITED THE TRACTOR COMPLETING A FULL WALK-AROUND INSPECTION OF THE UNIT. NEXT, HE PLACED CONES AROUND THE FUEL DROP AREA TO FORM A BARRIER AGAINST TRAFFIC. HE THEN GAUGED THE FUEL TANKS TO ENSURE THAT THERE WAS ENOUGH EMPTY SPACE IN THE TANK FOR THE AMOUNT THAT WAS TO BE DELIVERED AND TO ENSURE THAT THERE WAS NO WATER IN THE TANK. AFTER VERIFYING THAT THE PRODUCT WOULD FIT, HE REMOVED HIS VAPOR HOSE AND FITTING AND CONNECTED IT FROM THE OUTLET OF THE TRAILER TO THE OUTLET OF THE GROUND. AFTER THE VAPOR CONNECTION WAS COMPLETE, HE REMOVED HIS DROP HOSE AND FITTING FROM THE TRAILER TO CONNECT FROM THE TRAILER TO THE TANK. AFTER THE CONNECTIONS WERE MADE, HE PULLED THE DISCHARGE VALVE TO BEGIN DROPPING PRODUCT INTO THE TANK. SHORTLY AFTER THE PRODUCT BEGAN TO FLOW, THE DRIVER NOTICED THAT THE DROP FITTING CONNECTED TO THE TANK HAD COME UNLOCKED AND PRODUCT WAS SPILLING ONTO THE GROUND. HE IMMEDIATELY SHUT OFF THE DISCHARGE VALVE TO STOP THE FLOW OF PRODUCT. HE THEN GATHERED SPILL PADS AND PLACED THEM AT THE FURTHEST POINT AT WHERE THE SPILL HAD RAN AND THEN BEGAN TO SOAK UP THE SPILLED PRODUCT BACK TOWARDS THE DROP AREA. HE SOAKED UP ALL THE REMAINING PRODUCT AND WAITED ON THE CLEANUP CREW TO COME OUT AND DO AN INSPECTION AND FURTHER CLEANING IF NEEDED. LAW ENFORCEMENT AND EMERGENCY PERSONNEL WERE DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE WHERE THEY ROPED OFF THE AFFECTED AREA SO THAT THE SITE WOULD NOT BE FURTHER CONTAMINATED.
column169: AFTER THE SPILL OCCURRED, THE DRIVER WAS COACHED ON MAKING SURE THAT THE DROP CONNECTION WAS SECURE WITHOUT A DOUBT. HE WAS RETRAINED TO PULL ON THE FITTING TO MAKE SURE THAT THE CONNECTION TO THE TANK FITTING WAS SECURELY LOCKED BEFORE ATTEMPTING TO DISCHARGE PRODUCT. THE DROP FITTING THAT WAS USED DURING THIS INCIDENT WAS TAKEN OUT OF SERVICE TO ENSURE THAT IT DID NOT HAPPEN AGAIN. DRIVERS HAVE BEEN RETRAINED TO INSPECT AND MONITOR THEIR EQUIPMENT MORE FREQUENTLY TO HELP PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS OF THIS NATURE. ANY COMPANY THAT MAKES HAZMAT DELIVERIES SHOULD TAKE THE TIME TO COMPLETE EQUIPMENT INSPECTIONS ON A MORE FREQUENT BASIS TO MINIMIZE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

ON NOVEMBER 25, 2018, AT 7:13AM, A BOBTAIL DELIVERY TRUCK WAS TRAVELING ON MOUNTAIN ROAD IN GOFFSTOWN, NH WHEN THE DRIVER LOST CONTROL OF THE VEHICLE. THE TRUCK FLIPPED ON ITS' SIDE AND CAME TO REST AT THE BOTTOM OF A SLEEP SECTION OF THE ROAD. NO INJURIES WERE SUSTAINED TO THE DRIVER, HOWEVER, 1,136 GALLONS OF FUMACE (#2) OIL WAS RELEASED FROM THE CARGO TANK. FIRST RESPONDERS IMMEDIATELY WORKED TO STOP ANY ADDITIONAL PRODUCT RELEASE FROM THE CARGO TANK BY SECURING THE HATCHES ON TOP OF THE TRUCK. THEY ALSO BUILT BERMS AND DEPLOYED OIL ABSORBENT BOOMS TO MITIGATE THE MIGRATION OF THE PRODUCT THAT HAD ALREADY BEEN RELEASED.  THE GOFFSTOWN FIR DEPARTMENT & POLICE DEPARTMENT WERE THE FIRST TO SECURE THE SCENE. STATE POLICE RESPONDED LATER. THE FLOW OF PRODUCT WAS STOPPED UTILIZING BERMS OF SNOW, SAND AND OIL ABSORBENT PADS. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ALSO SECURED THE TRUCK FROM FURTHER DANGER BY INSTALLING SEVERAL STEEL BRACES ALONG THE TOP OF THE VEHICLE. IRVING CLEANUP CONTRACTOR NRC RESPONDED AT APPROXIMATELY 12:00PM TO BEGIN CLEAN UP EFFORTS UTILIZING EQUIPMENT THAT REMOVED IMPACTED SOLIDS AND LIQUIDS FROM THE SITE. CLEANUP EFFORTS AND STRATEGY WERE COORDINATED WITH THE DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES WHO HAD TWO REPRESENTATIVES ON SITE.
column169: ROOT CAUSE: THE GPS BEING USED BY THE DRIVER TO NAVIGATE, ROUTED HIM ONTO A ROAD THAT WAS COMPROMISED RESULTING IN A LOSS OF CONTROL OF THE VEHICLE.  OTHER CONTRIBUTING FACTORS: 1. DRIVER'S LACK OF FAMILIARITY WITH ROADS IN THAT AREA. 2. WEATHER CONDITIONS AND ELEVATION OF THE INCIDENT LOCATION CONTRIBUTED TO LESS THAN DESIRABLE ROAD CONDITIONS. 3. ROAD CONDITIONS WERE DIFFERENT IN VICINITY OF INCIDENT: - CHANGE IN MUNICIPALITIES AT JUNCTION NEARBY (TOP O HILL) WHERE ROADS WERE TREATED AND MAINTAINED DIFFERENTLY.  - INCIDENT OCCURRED IN REDUCED SALT ZONE DUE TO PROXIMITY OF NEARBY WATER RESERVOIR.  RECOMMENDED CORRECTIVE ACTIONS: 1. DETERMINE BEST PRACTICES FOR GPS USE. 2. EXPLORE ALTERNATIVE OPTIONS FOR ROUTING TECHNOLOGY. FOR EXAMPLE, GPS INTELLIGENCE NOT FOR SHORTEST ROUTE BUT SAFEST ROUTE. TECHNOLOGY WITH ABILITY TO BLOCK CERTAIN ROADS DEPENDING ON THE CONDITIONS AND/ OR TIME OF YEAR. INVESTIGATE FURTHER, THE RAVEN'S CAPABILITIES. 3. REINFORCE COMMUNICATION THAT IRVING HAS YOUR BACK TO NOT COMPLETE TICKET DUE TO WEATHER/ROAD CONDITIONS.

column168: UNIT 1 WITH UNIT 2 IN TOW WAS HEADING EAST ON HWY 21 IN THE INSIDE LANE WHEN HE APPROACHED THE INTERSECTION OF HWY 21 AND MARINO RD. UNIT 3 WAS LEAVING THE PARKING LOT OF A BAR DIRECTLY WEST ON THE CORNER OF HWY 21 AND MARINO RD., AND TURNED DIRECTLY IN FRONT OF UNITS 1 AND 2. STRIKING THE FRONT LEFT PART OF UNIT 1 WITH THE BACK RIGHT PORTION OF UNIT 3. THE COLLISION CAUSED UNITS 1 AND 2 TO ROLL ONTO ITS PASSENGER SIDE. DURING THE ROLLOVER UNIT 1 MADE CONTACT WITH A TRAFFIC SIGNAL CAUSING DAMAGE. ADDITIONALLY, THE COLLISION CAUSED A PUNCTURE IN THE TANKER APPROXIMATELY 4 INCHES WIDE ALLOWING THE CRUDE BEING TRANSPORTED TO BE RELEASED INTO THE SURROUNDING AREA. THE PUNCTURE IN THE TANKER WAS AGAINST THE ROAD AND INACCESSIBLE TO RESPONDING PERSONNEL. THE WAY THE EQUIPMENT CAME TO REST AFTER THE COLLISION PREVENTED THE ENTIRE LOAD FROM ESCAPING. CONSIDERING IT WAS A BUSY HIGHWAY, EMERGENCY PERSONNEL WERE NOTIFIED IMMEDIATELY, AND A SPILL RESPONSE TEAM WAS DISPATCHED 15 MINUTES AFTER RECEIVING THE NOTIFICATION.
column169: ALTHOUGH THE INVESTIGATION THAT FOLLOWED THIS ACCIDENT CLEARED US OF ANY FAULT, WE HAVE PLACED MORE EMPHASIS ON OUR DEFENSIVE AND DISTRACTED DRIVING PROGRAMS.

column169: THE MATERIAL CONTAINED A LOT OF SOLIDS AND THE PREPARRER LIKELY THOUGHT THAT THE METAL WOULD BE SUFFICIENT FOR THE MATERIAL IN TRANSIT. HOWEVER, LINER SHOULD HAVE BEEN UTILIZED TO ASSIST WITH PROTECTING THE DRUM FROM DAMAGE AND LEAKAGE. UTILIZING MATERIAL OF ANOTHER CONSTRUCTION WOULD HAVE BEEN A BETTER CHOICE OVERALL.

column168: CARRIER DRIVER DELIVERED 8,500 GALLONS TO MOLO GAS STATION AND THAT AMOUNT DID NOT FIT INTO THE TANK. 30-40 GALLONS SPILLED OUT THE FILL SUMP CONTAINMENT. AT TANK 90% FALL OVERFILL FLAP SHOULD HAVE PREVENTED PRODUCT FROM SPILLING. CARRIER DRIVER SHOULD HAVE ALSO USED HIS TANK MEASURING STICK TO GET A TANK READING.
column169: BEFORE UNLOADING CARRIER DRIVER SHOULD HAVE USED HIS TANK MEASURING STICK TO SEE IF PRODUCT AMOUNT HE BROUGHT WOULD FIT INTO THE TANK. OR IF AVAILABLE CHECK WITH THE GAS STATION FOR A VEEDER-ROOT READING WITH TANK AMOUNTS.

column168: DRIVER WAS DELIVERING GASOLINE TO A CASEY'S GAS STATION. HE WAS UNLOADING INTO 87 TANK. GASOLINE STARTED COMING OUT A SECOND FILL PIPE NEAR BY. THE DRIVER DID NOT KNOW THE TWO FILLS WERE FOR THE SAME GASOLINE (87) TANK AND IT HAD A MANIFOLD RUNNING BETWEEN THE TANKS. AS A RESULT GASOLINE (87) WAS GOING INTO ONE TANK AND THROUGH THE MANIFOLD AND FILLED UP THE ONE TANK BEFORE TANK LEVELS EVENED OUT.
column169: DRIVER SHOULD HAVE ASKED STORE MANAGER ABOUT THEIR TANKS OR CASEY'S STORE MANAGER SHOULD HAVE NOTIFIED DRIVER OF THEIR MANIFOLDED TANKS.
